<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="55" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="55">
This species was found on the hindgut lining of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" family="Baetidae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="family">Baetidae</taxonomicName>
hosts (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pictet" baseAuthorityYear="1843" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Baetis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Baetis rhodani" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhodani">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Baetis rhodani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Pictet, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pictet" baseAuthorityYear="1843" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Baetis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Baetis melanonyx" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melanonyx">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Baetis melanonyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Pictet) and 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. alpinus" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="alpinus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">B. alpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Pictet). The species seems to have a cosmopolitan distribution, at least in the Northern Hemisphere (
<bibRefCitation author="Lichtwardt, RW" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" refId="B26" refString="Lichtwardt, RW, Cafaro, MJ, White, MM, 2001. The trichomycetes, fungal associates of arthropods. Revised edition, published on the Internet. University of Kansas." title="The trichomycetes, fungal associates of arthropods. Revised edition, published on the Internet. University of Kansas." year="2001">Lichtwardt et al. 2001</bibRefCitation>
). In Europe, the species is common, with records from France, where it was originally described under the name of 
<taxonomicName authority="L.Léger. &amp; M.Gauthier, 1932" authorityName="L.Léger. &amp; M.Gauthier" authorityYear="1932" class="Kickxellomycetes" family="Legeriomycetaceae" genus="Genistella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Genistella ramosa" order="Harpellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Zygomycota" rank="species" species="ramosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Genistella ramosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="Léger">Leger</normalizedToken>
and Gauthier 1932) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02854735" author="Pouzar, Z" journalOrPublisher="Folia Geobotanica et Phytotaxonomica, Praha" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="319 - 320" refId="B46" refString="Pouzar, Z, 1972. Genistella Leger et Gauthier vs. Genistella Ortega; a nomenclatural note. Folia Geobotanica et Phytotaxonomica, Praha 7: 319 - 320, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02854735" title="Genistella Leger et Gauthier vs. Genistella Ortega; a nomenclatural note." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02854735" volume="7" year="1972">Pouzar 1972</bibRefCitation>
), from United Kingdom (
<bibRefCitation author="Moss, ST" editor="Lekh, RB" journalOrPublisher="Allanheld, Osmun and Co, Montclair" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="175 - 227" refId="B40" refString="Moss, ST, 1979. Commensalism of the Trichomycetes. In: Lekh, RB, Ed., Insect-fungus Symbiosis: Nutrition, Mutualism, and Commensalism. Allanheld, Osmun and Co, Montclair: 175 - 227" title="Commensalism of the Trichomycetes." volumeTitle="Insect-fungus Symbiosis: Nutrition, Mutualism, and Commensalism." year="1979">Moss 1979</bibRefCitation>
), Switzerland (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4612-4890-3" author="Lichtwardt, RW" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" refId="B23" refString="Lichtwardt, RW, 1986. The Trichomycetes: Fungal Associates of Arthropods. New York: Springer-Verlag, 343 pp. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4612-4890-3" title="The Trichomycetes: Fungal Associates of Arthropods. New York: Springer-Verlag, 343 pp." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4612-4890-3" year="1986">Lichtwardt 1986</bibRefCitation>
), Spain (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2003.11833239" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="321 - 326" refId="B64" refString="Valle, LG, Santamaria, S, 2002. Baetimyces, a new genus of Harpellales, and first report of Legeriomyces ramosus from the northeastern Iberian Peninsula. Mycologia 94: 321 - 326, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2003.11833239" title="Baetimyces, a new genus of Harpellales, and first report of Legeriomyces ramosus from the northeastern Iberian Peninsula." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2003.11833239" volume="94" year="2002">Valle and Santamaria 2002</bibRefCitation>
), Norway (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" author="White, MM" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="891 - 910" refId="B72" refString="White, MM, Lichtwardt, RW, 2004. Fungal symbionts (Harpellales) in Norwegian aquatic insect larvae. Mycologia 96: 891 - 910, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" title="Fungal symbionts (Harpellales) in Norwegian aquatic insect larvae." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" volume="96" year="2004">White and Lichtwardt 2004</bibRefCitation>
), Sweden (
<bibRefCitation author="Lichtwardt, RW" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="529 - 550" refId="B22" refString="Lichtwardt, RW, 1984. Species of Harpellales living within the guts of aquatic Diptera larvae. Mycotaxon 19: 529 - 550" title="Species of Harpellales living within the guts of aquatic Diptera larvae." volume="19" year="1984">Lichtwardt 1984</bibRefCitation>
), Portugal (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-211" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="748 - 759" refId="B59" refString="Valle, LG, 2013a. New and rare Harpellales from Portugal and northwestern Iberian Peninsula: discovering the hidden mycobiota of Galicia-Tras-os-Montes region. Mycologia 105: 748 - 759, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/12-211" title="New and rare Harpellales from Portugal and northwestern Iberian Peninsula: discovering the hidden mycobiota of Galicia-Tras-os-Montes region." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-211" volume="105" year="2013 a">Valle 2013a</bibRefCitation>
) and Italy (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-184" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="712 - 727" refId="B67" refString="Valle, LG, Rossi, W, Santamaria, S, 2013. New species and new records of trichomycetes from Italy. Mycologia 105: 712 - 727, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/12-184" title="New species and new records of trichomycetes from Italy." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-184" volume="105" year="2013">Valle et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pouzar" authorityYear="1972" class="Kickxellomycetes" family="Legeriomycetaceae" genus="Legeriomyces" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Legeriomyces ramosus" order="Harpellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Zygomycota" rank="species" species="ramosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Legeriomyces ramosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been reported also from India (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2008.11832501" author="Misra, JK" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="94 - 98" refId="B37" refString="Misra, JK, Tiwari, VK, 2008. A new species of Gauthieromyces and range extensions for other Harpellales in India. Mycologia 100: 94 - 98, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2008.11832501" title="A new species of Gauthieromyces and range extensions for other Harpellales in India." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2008.11832501" volume="100" year="2008">Misra and Tiwari 2008</bibRefCitation>
), China (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/09-029" author="Strongman, DB" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia," pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="174 - 184" refId="B51" refString="Strongman, DB, Wang, J, Xu, S, 2010. Trichomycetes from Western China. Mycologia, 102: 174 - 184, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/09-029" title="Trichomycetes from Western China." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/09-029" volume="102" year="2010">Strongman et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
), from several localities in USA (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4612-4890-3" author="Lichtwardt, RW" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" refId="B23" refString="Lichtwardt, RW, 1986. The Trichomycetes: Fungal Associates of Arthropods. New York: Springer-Verlag, 343 pp. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4612-4890-3" title="The Trichomycetes: Fungal Associates of Arthropods. New York: Springer-Verlag, 343 pp." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4612-4890-3" year="1986">Lichtwardt 1986</bibRefCitation>
) and Canada (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1139/B10-073" author="Strongman, DB" journalOrPublisher="Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="1011 - 1022" refId="B50" refString="Strongman, DB, 2010. Trichomycetes from Newfoundland, including Gros Morne National Park. Botany 88: 1011 - 1022, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1139/B10-073" title="Trichomycetes from Newfoundland, including Gros Morne National Park." url="https://doi.org/10.1139/B10-073" volume="88" year="2010">Strongman 2010</bibRefCitation>
). Bulgarian specimens have, as is usual in this species, a broad range of trichospore variability, measuring 30-40 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
7-8.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, with two appendages differing in length. Zygospores measure 50-61 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
9-12 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
in our collections (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 11–16" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 11 - 16. Various species of Harpellales. 11 - 13 Graminella microspora from Baetidae nymphs: 11 thallus overview, with inflated basal cell structures from which propagules arise or are extruded (note: one empty basal cell which has extruded its cellular content, arrow); young zygospores can also be observed (arrowhead) 12 a cluster of basal cells 13 fertile branch with a long series of minute trichospores; 14, 15 Harpella melusinae from Simuliidae larvae: 14 generative cells and allantoids or curved trichospores 15 basal cell and small conic holdfast 16 Legeriomyces ramosus from Baetidae nymphs, zygospores and zygosporophores. Scale bars: 25 μm in all figures." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.67.52055.figures11-16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/414541" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
